ions","id":"20226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20227"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43590"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107137"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the gynaecologist with a 2 year history of cyclical chronic pelvic pain and dysmenorrhoea. She no past medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination her vital signs are within normal limits and her abdominal and pelvic examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe gynaecologist arranges a diagnostic laparoscopy which reveals a 4 cm dark-coloured left ovarian cyst containing old blood when drained.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following conditions is most likely to cause this type of ovarian cyst?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endometriosis","Polycystic ovary syndrome","Follicular cyst","Dermoid cyst","Cystadenoma"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an endometrioma, also known as a chocolate cyst, which is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometriosis\u003C/strong\u003E. These cysts form when endometrial tissue grows within the ovary and undergoes cyclical bleeding, leading to accumulation of old blood that gives them their characteristic chocolate-brown appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic ovary syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with multiple small follicular cysts rather than blood-filled cysts. \u003Cstrong\u003EFollicular cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are clear and fluid-filled, arising from unruptured follicles. \u003Cstrong\u003EDermoid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E contain various tissue types including hair and sebaceous material. \u003Cstrong\u003ECystadenomas\u003C/strong\u003E are typically clear or straw-coloured fluid-filled tumours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endometriosis commonly forms ovarian cysts called endometriomas or chocolate cysts due to accumulated menstrual blood.","Chocolate cysts appear brown due to the presence of old blood and tissue."],"references":["Burney RO, Giudice LC. Pathogenesis and pathophysiology of endometriosis. Fertil Steril. 2012 Sep;98(3):511-9. doi: 10.1016/j.fertnstert.2012.06.029. Epub 2012 Jul 20. PMID: 22819144; PMCID: PMC3836682.","Parasar P, Ozcan P, Terry KL. Endometriosis: Epidemiology, Diagnosis and Clinical Management. Curr Obstet Gynecol Rep. 2017 Mar;6(1):34-41. doi: 10.1007/s13669-017-0187-1. Epub 2017 Jan 27. PMID: 29276652; PMCID: PMC5737931.","Smolarz B, Szy\u0142\u0142o K, Romanowicz H. Endometriosis: Epidemiology, Classification, Pathogenesis, Treatment and Genetics (Review of Literature). Int J Mol Sci. 2021 Sep 29;22(19):10554. doi: 10.3390/ijms221910554. PMID: 34638893; PMCID: PMC8508982.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89605"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15703"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89605"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T15:29:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T15:29:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8394"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107137"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda